rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/4b255fc4-33d3-4beb-a238-37e1a8cf32a2">     <title>Windermere pike fecundity and egg data 1963-2003</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/4b255fc4-33d3-4beb-a238-37e1a8cf32a2</link>     <description>This dataset consists of fecundity, egg and associated data on female pike (Esox lucius) from net sampling in Windermere. Data collection began in 1963. The data were initially collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA) but have been collected by the Centre for Ecology and Hydrology and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE) since 1989.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Claire Wood</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>fish</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Water resources</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2015-03-16T09:25:36Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/ed05bf51-c3be-46f9-a1af-2e0789273bd5">     <title>Windermere perch data 1946-2012</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/ed05bf51-c3be-46f9-a1af-2e0789273bd5</link>     <description>This series of datasets consists of monthly mean inshore surface water temperature (degrees C) data from Windermere,  total weekly catch data of mature Perch (Perca fluviatilis) from trapping at Green Tuft, Windermere and weekly mean sizes of Perch from trapping at Green Tuft, Windermere.  The data presented were sampled between 1946 and 2012 from Windermere, a lake in northern England. The data were collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA) and then by the Centre for Ecology and Hydrology and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE).  The files available in this series were used in Ohlberger et al. (2014) Proceedings of the Royal Society B (When phenology matters: Age-size truncation alters population response to trophic mismatch). </description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Claire Wood</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Lake District</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>freshwater</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>monthly</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>fish</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>water temperature</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>perch</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2014-08-14T10:33:30Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/58357e70-d79b-4149-aa02-762c20b01198">     <title>Pike 1944-2002</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/58357e70-d79b-4149-aa02-762c20b01198</link>     <description>This series of datasets consists of growth (length) data, survival data and fecundity data for Pike (Esox lucius) from net sampling in Windermere. Lake temperature data is also part of the series.  Data collection began in 1944. The data were initially collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA) but have been collected by CEH and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE) since 1989.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Hannah Dean</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2013-09-16T14:34:30Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/9520664c-eb4d-4700-b064-5d215d23e595">     <title>Windermere lake temperature data 1944-2002</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/9520664c-eb4d-4700-b064-5d215d23e595</link>     <description>This dataset consists of inshore surface water temperature (degrees C) data on Windermere. Data collection began in 1933, but it presented here from 1944 onwards. The data were initially collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA), then by CEH and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE) from 1989 to 2003, and subsequently again by FBA.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Claire Wood</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2013-09-09T14:31:03Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/813e07dd-2135-49bc-93c6-83999e442b36">     <title>Pike survival data 1953-1990</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/813e07dd-2135-49bc-93c6-83999e442b36</link>     <description>This dataset consists of survival (binary) data derived from capture-mark-recapture on Pike (Esox lucius) from net and angling sampling in Windermere. Data collection began in 1944. The data were initially collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA) but have been collected by CEH and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE) since 1989.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Claire Wood</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2013-09-09T14:29:14Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/637d60d6-1571-49af-93f7-24c1279d884d">     <title>Pike growth data 1944-1995</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/637d60d6-1571-49af-93f7-24c1279d884d</link>     <description>This dataset consists of growth (length) data on Pike (Esox lucius) from net sampling in Windermere. Data collection began in 1944. The data were initially collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA) but have been collected by CEH and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE) since 1989.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Claire Wood</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2013-09-09T14:18:56Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/b8886915-14cb-44df-86fa-7ab718acf49a">     <title>Pike fecundity data 1963-2002</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/b8886915-14cb-44df-86fa-7ab718acf49a</link>     <description>This dataset consists of fecundity (number of eggs) data on Pike (Esox lucius) from net sampling in Windermere. Data collection began in 1963. The data were initially collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA) but have been collected by CEH and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE) since 1989.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Claire Wood</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2013-09-09T13:57:07Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/f3f3ba40-c655-4740-b9b4-ce77ab286fb0">     <title>Windermere fish abundance 1940-2012</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/f3f3ba40-c655-4740-b9b4-ce77ab286fb0</link>     <description>This dataset consists of information regarding the abundance of fish species from Windermere, and includes long-term data on Arctic Charr (Salvelinus alpinus), Pike (Esox lucius), Perch (Perca fluviatilis) and some recent data on Roach (Rutilus rutilus) from net and trap sampling, together with data on total fish abundance from hydroacoustics. Data collection began in 1940. With the exception of the hydroacoustics, the data were initially collected by the Freshwater Biological Association (FBA) but have been collected by CEH and its predecessor Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE) since 1989.  The hydroacoustics data have been collected by CEH/IFE since 1990.  The data available to download originate from Windermere North and South Basins and are given as yearly averages.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Claire Wood</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Species distribution</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Cumbria</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Lake District</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Windermere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Annual</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2013-04-19T14:42:44Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     </rdf:RDF>
